This project features a Python-based Mock Sensor designed to simulate real-time water telemetry for the Grand Marina Hydrologic System. 
By generating synthetic data that mimics physical hardware, this simulator allows for the cost-effective testing of monitoring dashboards and security protocols without the need for expensive physical deployments. 
The WaterSensor class produces realistic data packets including flow rate, upstream/downstream pressure, and ISO 8601 UTC timestamps. 
To ensure authenticity, it incorporates stochastic variation—or "jitter"—to replicate the natural fluctuations found in real-world sensing equipment.Beyond normal operations, the simulator can inject three distinct failure states derived from the STRIDE Threat Model to test system resilience. 
These anomalies include Leak Simulation (High Flow), Blockage Simulation (Pressure Differentials), and Stuck Sensors (System Blindness), which are essential for validating how the Cloud API and Web Dashboard handle critical alerts. 
All generated telemetry is exported to a structured JSON format, providing a ready-to-use dataset for auditing system behavior and ensuring that no unauthorized changes go undetected.
